INTERCONNECTION AND TRANSMISSION SERVICE AGREEMENT This Interconnection and Transmission Service Agreement (Agreement) is made and entered into as of August 21, 2020, by and between Smoky Mountain Transmission LLC (SMT), a limited liability company organized and existing under the laws of the State of Delaware, and Brookfield Smoky Mountain Hydropower LP (BSMH), a limited partnership organized and existing under the laws of the State of Delaware; each a Party and collectively, the Parties. RECITALS WHEREAS, BSMH owns and operates an approximately 392 MW hydroelectric project (BSMH Project) located in eastern Tennessee and western North Carolina consisting of four individual hydroelectric developments: (i) Calderwood (156 MW); (ii) Cheoah (143 MW); (iii) Chilhowee (51 MW); and (iv) Santeetlah (42 MW) (collectively, the Generating Facilities). WHEREAS, SMT owns and operates approximately 86 miles of 161 kV limited and discrete transmission lines and related facilities (the SMT Facilities) located in the Tennessee Valley Authority (TVA) balancing authority area that connect the Generating Facilities to each other and to the transmission systems owned and operated by TVA and Duke Energy Carolinas, LLC (Duke). WHEREAS, currently, SMT provides, and BSMH receives, interconnection service and transmission service for the full output of the Generating Facilities pursuant to the following service agreements under SMTs Open Access Transmission Tariff: the Standard Large Generator Interconnection Agreement (LGIA) between SMT and BSMH entered into on January 6, 2014 pursuant to which the Calderwood hydroelectric development interconnects to the SMT Facilities, the LGIA between SMT and BSMH entered into on January 6, 2014 pursuant to which the Cheoah hydroelectric development interconnects to the SMT Facilities, the LGIA between SMT and BSMH entered into on January 6, 2014 pursuant to which the Chilhowee hydroelectric development interconnects to the SMT Facilities, the LGIA between SMT and BSMH entered into on January 6, 2014 pursuant to which the Santeetlah hydroelectric development interconnects to the SMT Facilities, and the Service Agreement for Firm Point-To-Point Transmission Service between SMT and BSMH entered into on June 12, 2014 pursuant to which SMT provides firm point-to-point transmission service to BSMH on the SMT Facilities (collectively, the OATT Agreements). WHEREAS, SMT desires to cancel its Open Access Transmission Tariff and provide interconnection service and Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service (as defined herein) to BSMH pursuant to the terms of this Agreement. WHEREAS, SMT and BSMH have agreed to amend and restate the OATT Agreements in the form of this Agreement to allow (i) BSMH to continue to interconnect the Generating Facilities to the SMT Facilities, and (ii) SMT to continue to provide BSMH with Firm Point- to-Point Transmission Service over the SMT Facilities to deliver the full output of the Generating Facilities to the transmission systems of TVA and/or Duke, as applicable. NOW, THEREFORE, the parties hereto agree as follows: ARTICLE 1 DEFINITIONS For the purposes of this Agreement, the following words and terms shall have the meanings specified below: Agreement has the meaning given in the preamble to the Agreement. Applicable Laws means all laws, treaties, ordinances, statutes, judgments, injunctions, decrees, orders, writs, rules, regulations and interpretations of any Governmental Authority to the extent they apply to the actions of the Parties.
Applicable Reliability Standards shall mean the requirements and guidelines of the North American Electric Reliability Corporation or any of its regional entities. BSMH has the meaning given in the preamble to the Agreement. BSMH Project has the meaning given in the recitals to the Agreement. Confidential Information has the meaning given in Section 10.2.
Curtailment means a reduction of the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service in response to a transmission capacity shortage as a result of system reliability conditions, in accordance with Section 2.6. Duke has the meaning given in the recitals to the Agreement. Duke IA means the Interconnection Agreement between SMT and Duke dated September 1, 2013, as amended from time to time. Duke Point of Delivery means the point(s) of interconnection between the SMT Facilities and Dukes transmission system as set forth in the Duke IA. Effective Date has the meaning given in Section 3.1 of the Agreement. Event of Default has the meaning given in Section 6.1 of the Agreement. FERC means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, or any successor agency. Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service has the meaning given in Section 2.2 of the Agreement. Force Majeure has the meaning given in Section 4.1 of the Agreement. FPA means the Federal Power Act, as amended, and FERCs implementing regulations thereunder. Generating Facilities has the meaning given in the recitals to the Agreement. 2 Good Utility Practice means any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather to be acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region, including those practices required by FPA section 215(a)(4). Governmental Authority means any national, state or local government, any political subdivision thereof, or any governmental, quasi-governmental, judicial, public or statutory instrumentality, administrative agency, authority, body or other entity having jurisdiction over a Party or its operations. Indemnified Party has the meaning given in Section 5.1 of the Agreement. Indemnitor has the meaning given in Section 5.1 of the Agreement. Interconnection Facilities shall mean all facilities and equipment between each Generating Facility and its Point of Interconnection. Maximum Facility Output means the maximum (not nominal) net electrical power output in megawatts, specified in Appendix A to this Agreement, after supply of any parasitic or host facility loads, that each Generating Facility is expected to produce. O&M Agreements mean (i) the Management and Operating Agreement between SMT and Smoky Mountain Holdings LLC (Smoky Mountain Holdings) dated as of November 15, 2012 and (ii) the Management and Operating Agreement between Smoky Mountain Holdings and Brookfield Power US Asset Management LLC dated as of November 15, 2012 as amended by the First Amendment to the Management and Operating Agreement dated as of November 17, 2014, pursuant to which SMT receives management, administrative, operation and maintenance services with respect to the SMT Facilities, as amended from time to time. Party and Parties has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. Person means any individual, corporation, partnership, limited liability company, association, joint stock company, trust, unincorporated organization, joint venture, government or political subdivision or agency therefore, Governmental Authority, or any other entity or organization.
Point of Interconnection shall mean each point, as set forth in Figure A-1 to Appendix A, where BSMHs Interconnection Facilities for each Generating Facility connect to SMTs Interconnection Facilities. Points of Receipt means SMTs side of the Points of Interconnection for the Generating Facilities as identified in Appendix A. SMT has the meaning given in the preamble to the Agreement. 3 SMT Facilities has the meaning given in the recitals to the Agreement. TVA means Tennessee Valley Authority, or any successor agency. TVA IA means the Interconnection Agreement between TVA and Alcoa Power Generating Inc. dated as of May 20, 2011, as amended and supplemented by the Assignment and Amendatory Agreement among TVA, Alcoa Power Generating Inc., SMT and BSMH dated as of November 15, 2012, as amended from time to time. TVA Point of Delivery means the point(s) of interconnection between the SMT Facilities and TVAs transmission system as set forth in the TVA IA. ARTICLE 2 SERVICES 2.1 Interconnection. SMT will permit BSMH to interconnect each Generating Facility to the SMT Facilities at the Point of Interconnection identified in Appendix A. SMT will cooperate with BSMH to effectuate and maintain such interconnections in accordance with this Agreement. 2.1.1 Each Party shall operate, maintain, repair and inspect, and shall be fully responsible for, the facilities that it now or hereafter may own, in accordance with this Agreement, Applicable Reliability Standards and Good Utility Practice. 2.1.2 Each Party will operate its respective facilities in such a manner so as to not unreasonably interfere with the operation of the other Partys facilities. 2.1.3 Each Party will notify the other Party as soon as practicable of any emergency or hazardous condition or occurrence with its equipment or facilities that could affect safe operation of the SMT Facilities or the Generating Facilities, as applicable, and the Parties shall use reasonable efforts to promptly take appropriate action to eliminate the adverse effect. 2.1.4 Each Party shall have the right to temporarily disconnect its facilities from those of the other Party without prior notification in cases where, in the reasonable judgment of such Party, continuance of service under this Agreement is imminently likely to endanger persons or damage property. The disconnecting Party shall promptly notify the other Party of the emergency condition. To the extent information is known, the notification shall describe the emergency condition, the extent of the damage or deficiency, the expected effect on the operation of both Parties facilities and operations, its anticipated duration, and the necessary corrective action. Any curtailment, reduction or disconnection shall continue only for so long as reasonably necessary. The Parties shall cooperate with each other to restore the affected facilities to their normal operating state as soon as reasonably practicable following the cessation or remedy of the event that led to the temporary disconnection. 2.1.5 BSMH and SMT, as appropriate, shall maintain equipment that adequately protects their respective facilities, any affected transmission systems and other persons from damage or injury.
4 2.2 Firm Point-to-Point Transmission. BSMH shall be entitled to use the capacity of the SMT Facilities on a firm basis to transmit and deliver the full amount of electric energy generated by the Generating Facilities, up to 392 MW, from the Points of Receipt to either the Duke Point of Delivery or the TVA Point of Delivery, and to deliver electricity from a provider of station service to the Generating Facilities (the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service). Other than the obligation to pay expenses pursuant to Section 2.9, there shall be no charge to BSMH for the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service.
2.3 BSMH Reservation Priority. Long-term firm point-to-point transmission service on the SMT Facilities is made available on a first-come, first-served basis, i.e., in the chronological sequence in which each transmission customer has reserved service. Subsequent reservations for firm point-to-point transmission service on the SMT Facilities will be available only to the extent that there is transmission capability on the SMT Facilities in excess of the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service and in accordance with Applicable Reliability Standards, unless otherwise ordered by FERC. 2.4 Scheduling. No scheduling services currently are required for the Firm Point-to- Point Transmission Service provided under this Agreement. BSMH shall make all necessary scheduling arrangements with TVA and Duke, as applicable, to accept electric energy generated by the Generating Facilities at the TVA Point of Delivery and Duke Point of Delivery, as applicable. 2.5 Availability. SMT acknowledges that BSMHs rights to access and utilize the SMT Facilities on a firm basis is essential to the administration, operation and maintenance of the Generating Facilities. SMT shall comply at all times with the requirements of the TVA IA and Duke IA, and shall operate and maintain the SMT Facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practice. SMT shall coordinate any outages of the SMT Facilities as follows: (a) SMT shall coordinate with BSMH with respect to scheduling any planned outages of the SMT Facilities with the goal of scheduling planned outages during periods which minimize the impact on the operations of the Generating Facilities. (b) SMT shall give notice to BSMH as soon as practicable of any unplanned outages of the SMT Facilities. SMT shall work to restore the SMT Facilities to normal operating condition as quickly as possible.
2.6 Curtailment. The Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service may be subject to Curtailment to the extent necessary to maintain reliable operation of the SMT Facilities or the transmission systems directly and indirectly interconnected with the SMT Facilities. When SMT determines that an electrical emergency exists on the SMT Facilities and implements emergency procedures to curtail the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service, BSMH shall make the required reductions upon the request of SMT in accordance with Good Utility Practice. SMT reserves the right to curtail, in whole or in part, the Firm Point-to-Point Transmission Service provided under this Agreement when, in SMTs sole discretion, an emergency or other unforeseen condition impairs or degrades the reliability of the SMT Facilities. SMT will provide BSMH with advance notice of Curtailment where such notice can be provided consistent with Good Utility Practice.
5 2.7 Ancillary Services. BSMH shall be responsible for procuring or self-supplying electricity necessary for the operation of the Generating Facilities and any other ancillary services necessary to support the transmission of energy over the SMT Facilities while maintaining reliable operation of the SMT Facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practice.
2.8 Line Losses. BSMH shall be responsible for its line losses on the SMT Facilities.
2.9 Charges. As consideration for its rights hereunder, BSMH shall reimburse SMT for: (a) all expenses necessary for the operation and maintenance of the SMT Facilities including, but not limited to: (i) all fees and expenses payable under the O&M Agreements; (ii) insurance expenses; (iii) property or other ad valorem taxes assessed or allocated to the SMT Facilities; and (iv) the costs of obtaining and maintaining licenses and permits, and (b) any annual charges imposed on SMT by FERC pursuant to 18 C.F.R. § 382.201 if applicable as a result of providing service to BSMH under this Agreement. ARTICLE 3 -- TERM AND TERMINATION
3.1 Effective Date. The terms of this Agreement, and any amendment hereto, are subject to approval or acceptance for filing by FERC. This Agreement shall become effective upon such date as specified by FERC (the Effective Date). 3.2 Term. Service under this Agreement shall continue in effect from and after the Effective Date for an initial term of thirty (30) years (Initial Term), and shall be automatically renewed for each successive one-year period thereafter, unless earlier terminated by: (a) written mutual agreement of the Parties; or (b) in accordance with Article 6 for an Event of Default. 3.3 Governmental Approvals for Termination. Notwithstanding anything in this Agreement to the contrary, termination of this Agreement shall not become effective until the Parties have complied with all Applicable Laws to effectuate such termination, including obtaining any necessary authorization from FERC. 3.4 Survival Rights. Termination of this Agreement (a) shall not relieve either Party of any obligation hereunder which expressly or by implication survives termination hereof, including all indemnity obligations, and (b) except as otherwise provided in any provision of this Agreement expressly limiting the liability of either Party, shall not relieve either Party of any obligations or liabilities for loss or damage to the other Party arising out of or caused by any breach of this Agreement of such Party prior to the effectiveness of such termination or arising out of such termination.

ARTICLE 4 -- FORCE MAJEURE 4.1 Excuse. Neither Party shall be considered in default under this Agreement for any delay or failure in the performance of its obligations and shall be excused in the performance of its obligations under this Agreement if such delay or failure is due to an event of Force Majeure. Force Majeure means any event or circumstance, including any of the following enumerated events, that occur before the termination of this Agreement and that delays or prevents a Partys performance of its obligations under this Agreement, but only to the extent that (i) such event of Force Majeure is not attributable to fault or negligence on the part of that Party, (ii) such event of Force Majeure is caused by factors beyond that Partys reasonable control, and (iii) despite taking all reasonable technical and commercial precautions and measures to prevent, avoid, mitigate or overcome such event and the consequences thereof, the Party affected has been unable to prevent, avoid, mitigate or overcome such event or consequences: (a) Acts of God such as storms, hurricanes, floods, lightning and earthquakes; (b) Sabotage or destruction by a third-party of facilities and equipment relating to the performance by the affected Party of its obligations under this Agreement; (c) War, riot, acts of a public enemy or other civil disturbance; (d) Strike, walkout, lockout or other significant labor dispute; or (e) Action or inaction of a Governmental Authority. 4.2 Conditions. A Party may rely on a claim of Force Majeure to excuse its performance only to the extent that such Party: (a) Provides prompt notice of such Force Majeure event to the other Party, giving an estimate of its expected duration and the probable impact on the performance of its obligations under this Agreement; (b) Exercises all reasonable efforts to continue to perform its obligations under this Agreement; (c) Expeditiously takes action to correct or cure the event or condition excusing performance so that the suspension of performance is no greater in scope and no longer in duration than is dictated by the event or condition being corrected or cured using commercially reasonable efforts; provided, however, that settlement of strikes or other labor disputes will be completely within the sole discretion of the Party affected by such strike or labor dispute; (d) Exercises all commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate or limit damages to the other Party; and
7 (e) Provides prompt notice to the other Party of the cessation of the event or condition giving rise to its excuse from performance. ARTICLE 5 -- INDEMNIFICATION 5.1 General Indemnity. Each Party (an Indemnitor) shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Party (an Indemnified Party) and its respective directors, managers, officers, agents, employees, successors and assigns from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses (including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys and consultants fees), which may be imposed upon or incurred by such Party or asserted against such Party by any third person or entity in connection with this Agreement, the use of the SMT Facilities, or the operation and maintenance of the SMT Facilities or the Generating Facilities, to the extent such liabilities are caused by the gross negligence or intentionally wrongful acts or omissions of any of the Indemnitor, its contractors or their respective employees or agents. Any amount owing to an Indemnified Party under this Section 5.1 shall be the amount of such Indemnified Partys actual loss, net of any insurance or other recovery. 5.2 Indemnification Procedure. Promptly after receipt by an Indemnified Party of any claim or notice of the commencement of any action or administrative or legal proceeding or investigation as to which the indemnity provided for in Section 5.1 may apply, the Indemnified Party shall notify the Indemnitor of such fact. The Indemnitor shall assume on behalf of the Indemnified Party and conduct with due diligence and in good faith the defense of any claim against the Indemnified Party, whether or not the Indemnitor shall be joined therein, and the Indemnified Party shall cooperate with the Indemnitor in such defense. If the Indemnitor fails, after notice and reasonable opportunity to proceed under this article, to assume the defense of such claim, the Indemnified Party may, at the expense of the Indemnitor, contest, settle or consent to the entry of any judgment with respect to, or pay in full, such claim. 5.3 Comparative Negligence. If any liability, claim, loss or damage is caused by the joint or concurrent negligence of the Parties hereto or others for which they are responsible, responsibility for such liability, claim, loss or damage shall be apportioned on the basis of comparative fault principles.
5.4 Limitation of Liability. In no event shall either Party, or an officer, director, member, partner, shareholder, employee, agent or Affiliate of either Party, be liable for special, indirect, exemplary, punitive or consequential damages of any nature whatsoever arising out of this Agreement, including damages or claims in the nature of lost revenue, income or profits, loss of use, or cost of capital, irrespective of whether such damages are reasonably foreseeable and irrespective of whether such claims are based upon negligence, strict liability, contract, operation of law or otherwise; provided, however, that the limitation of liability imposed by this Section 5.4 shall not apply to (a) any Partys indemnity obligations set forth in Section 5.1 as they relate to claims by third parties, or (b) claims which arise or result from fraud, willful misconduct or gross negligence of a Party or any agent, subcontractor or vendor of such Party.
8 ARTICLE 6 -- DEFAULT; REMEDIES 6.1 Event of Default. For purposes of this Agreement, failure by a Party to comply with any material provision of this Agreement shall constitute an Event of Default if such Party fails to cure or remedy the breach within sixty (60) days after written notice and demand by the affected Party to cure the same or such longer period reasonably required to cure mutually agreed upon in writing, provided, however, that the defaulting Party diligently continues to cure until such failure is fully cured. No Event of Default shall exist where such failure to discharge an obligation is the result of Force Majeure as defined in this Agreement or the result of an act or omission of the other Party. 6.2 Remedies. If an Event of Default is not cured as provided in Section 6.1, or if an Event of Default is not capable of being cured within the period provided for herein, the non- defaulting Party shall have the right to terminate this Agreement by thirty (30) days written notice at any time until cure occurs, and be relieved of any further obligation hereunder and, whether or not that Party terminates this Agreement, to recover from the defaulting Party all amounts due hereunder, plus all other damages and remedies to which it is entitled at law or in equity. The provisions of this article will survive termination of this Agreement.
ARTICLE 7 ASSIGNMENT; TRANSFERS 7.1 Assignment. This Agreement may be assigned by a Party to other parties only upon the prior written consent of the other Party hereto, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed; provided, however, no consent shall be required in connection with any assignment of this Agreement for collateral security purposes. When duly assigned in accordance with the foregoing, this Agreement shall be binding upon and shall inure to the benefit of the assignee; any other assignment shall be void and without force or effect. 7.2 Transfers. A Party shall not transfer, sell, assign, sublease or otherwise dispose of its equity ownership interest in its respective facilities without the prior written consent of the other Party, which shall not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. In the event of a transfer of all or substantially all of a Partys equity ownership interest in its facilities, this Agreement shall be binding on the new owner(s) of such facilities. ARTICLE 8 REPRESENTATIONS AND WARRANTIES 8.1 Representations and Warranties of the Parties. As a material inducement to entry by the other Party into this Agreement, each Party, with respect to itself, hereby represents and warrants to the other Party as follows:
(a) it is duly organized, validly existing and in good standing under Applicable Laws of the jurisdiction of its formation and is qualified to conduct its business in those jurisdictions necessary to perform this Agreement; (b) its execution, delivery and performance hereof are within its statutory and limited liability company or limited partnership powers, have been duly authorized by all necessary action and do not conflict with or result in a breach of or default (with or without notice 9 or lapse of time or both) under any terms or conditions in its governing documents or any contract, agreement or instrument to which it is a party or any Applicable Laws by which it or any of its properties are bound; (c) this Agreement has been duly executed and delivered on its behalf by a duly authorized representative of such Party; (d) except for those already obtained and in full force and effect as of the Effective Date, no consent, approval, permit or other authorization from any Person is required for the performance by such Party of its obligations hereunder; (e) this Agreement constitutes a legal, valid and binding obligation of such Party enforceable against it in accordance with its terms, subject to bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization, moratorium or other Applicable Laws affecting creditors rights generally, and with regard to equitable remedies, to equitable defenses and discretion of the court before which proceedings to obtain such remedies may be pending; (f) there are no bankruptcy, insolvency, reorganization, receivership or other arrangement proceedings pending or being contemplated by it, or to its knowledge threatened against it; and (g) there are no suits, proceedings, judgments, rulings or orders by or before any Governmental Authority that materially adversely affect its ability to perform this Agreement. ARTICLE 9 DISPUTE RESOLUTION 9.1 Dispute Resolution. Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement, in the event a dispute arises between the Parties regarding the application or interpretation of any provision of this Agreement, the Party alleging the dispute shall promptly notify the other Party of the dispute in writing. If the Parties shall have failed to resolve the dispute within ten (10) days after delivery of such written notice, each Party shall, within five (5) days of receipt of a written demand from the other Party to do so, direct a senior management individual to confer in good faith within five (5) days with a senior management individual of the other Party to resolve the dispute. Should the Parties be unable to resolve the dispute to their mutual satisfaction within thirty (30) days, each Party may exercise whatever rights and remedies it may have in equity or law consistent with the terms of this Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Parties may at any time seek injunctive relief from a court of competent jurisdiction, and nothing herein shall prevent a Party from defending or pursuing any claim in a court or other proceeding against a third party that has been initiated by such third party. In the event any dispute involves common issues of fact, liability or responsibility with any dispute or controversy under any other agreement materially related to the SMT Facilities, each of the Parties agrees, where reasonably justified, to join such dispute with such other disputes and controversies to seek a common resolution of all such matters. ARTICLE 10 GENERAL PROVISIONS 10.1 Notices. Any notice required or authorized to be given hereunder or any other communications between the Parties shall be in writing (unless otherwise provided) and shall be deemed properly given if delivered in person, delivered by reputable national courier service, or 10 sent by first-class mail, postage prepaid, to the relevant Party at the address specified below. Any notice given personally shall be deemed to have been served on delivery, any notice so given by courier service shall be deemed to have been served two (2) working days after the same shall have been delivered to the relevant courier, and any notice so given by first-class mail shall be deemed to have been served five (5) working days after the same shall have been delivered to the postal service. Confidential information (Confidential Information) shall include, without limitation, any confidential and/or proprietary information provided by a Party to the other Party that is clearly marked or otherwise designated Confidential. For purposes of this Agreement, all design, operating specifications and metering data provided by a Party shall be deemed Confidential Information regardless of whether it is clearly marked or otherwise designated as such. Each Party receiving Confidential Information shall hold such information in confidence and shall not disclose it to any third party nor to the public without the prior written authorization from the Party providing that information, except to fulfill obligations under this Agreement, or to fulfill legal or regulatory requirements. Each Party shall employ at least the same standard of care to protect Confidential Information obtained from the other Party as it employs to protect its own Confidential Information. If disclosure of Confidential Information of a Party protected by this paragraph is sought through process of a court, or a state or federal regulatory agency or through other means of legal compulsion, or through a request for information made by the executive or legislative branches of the federal or a state government, the Party receiving such request will notify the other Party immediately so as to afford such other Party the opportunity to oppose such disclosure or otherwise obtain a protective order or other relief as may be available. The Party receiving such disclosure request will cooperate with the other Party in its attempts to obtain such protections. Each Party is entitled to equitable relief, by 11 injunction or otherwise, to enforce its rights under this provision to prevent the release of Confidential Information without bond or proof of damages and may seek other remedies available at law or in equity for breach of this provision. 10.3 Amendment. Any changes to this Agreement shall require the written approval of the Parties and shall be subject to FERC approval; provided, however, that, at any time that BSMH will no longer be the sole customer using the SMT Facilities, SMT shall revise Section 2.7 to reflect a pro rata allocation of such costs and expenses and shall timely make any required filings with FERC with respect to such amendment. 10.4 Construction. The language in all parts of this Agreement shall be in all cases construed simply according to its fair meaning and not strictly for or against any Party hereto. 10.5 Severability. If any provision or portion of this Agreement shall for any reason be held or adjudged to be invalid or illegal or unenforceable by any court of competent jurisdiction (i) such portion or provision shall be deemed separate and independent, (ii) the Parties shall negotiate in good faith to restore insofar as practicable the benefits to each Party that were affected by such ruling, and (iii) the remainder of this Agreement shall remain in full force and effect. 10.6 Governing Law. The terms and provisions of this Agreement shall be interpreted in accordance with the laws of the State of New York and without regard to the choice or conflicts of law principles of the State of New York or any other state (except for Section 5- 1401 of the New York General Obligations Law). 10.7 Waiver. The failure of a Party at any time to require performance by the other Party of any provision hereof shall not affect in any way the full right to require such performance at any time thereafter, nor shall the waiver by a Party of any breach of any provision hereof be held or deemed to be a waiver of the provision itself.
10.8 No Third-Party Beneficiaries. This Agreement is not intended to and does not create rights, remedies or benefits of any character whatsoever in favor of any persons, corporations, associations or entities other than the Parties, and the obligations herein assumed are solely for the use and benefit of the Parties, their successors in interest and where permitted, their assigns. 10.9 Further Assurances. Each Party agrees to provide such information, execute and deliver any instruments and documents and take such other actions as may be necessary or reasonably requested by the other Party that are not inconsistent with the provisions of this Agreement and that do not involve the assumption of obligations other than those provided for in this Agreement, in order to give full effect to this Agreement and to carry out the intent of this Agreement. 10.10 Entire Agreement. This Agreement shall constitute the entire agreement and understanding between the Parties with reference to the subject matter hereof, and supersedes all prior and contemporaneous understandings or agreements, oral or written, between the Parties with respect to the subject matter of this Agreement. 12 10.11 Multiple Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed and delivered electronically in two or more counterparts, each of which is deemed an original but all constitute one and the same instrument.

Description of Interconnections The BSMH Project consists of four individual hydroelectric developments: (1) Calderwood, (2) Cheoah, (3) Chilhowee, and (4) Santeetlah. FERC originally granted the BSMH Project a 50-year license in 1955, and in 2005 FERC granted the Project another 40-year license, allowing it to remain in operation until 2045. This Agreement continues the existing interconnection of each of the Generating Facilities to the SMT Facilities. All of the Interconnection Facilities identified in this Appendix A are existing facilities. No new Interconnection Facilities are required to be constructed under this Agreement. A. Calderwood Calderwood is an existing hydroelectric plant located on the Little Tennessee River in Tennessee. Based on the plants historical operations and proven ability to deliver power to the SMT Facilities, Calderwood has a Maximum Facility Output of 156 MW. 1. Point of Interconnection. The Point of Interconnection for the Calderwood hydroelectric plant is at the point where the plants GSU 161/13.8 kV transformer high-side bushings connect with the SMTs 161 kV facilities as shown in Figure A-1. At Calderwood Units G1 G3, this is at the termination to SMTs 161 kV bus. 2. BSMHs Interconnection Facilities (including metering equipment). III. Additional Requirements
A. Metering
Each Party shall comply with the Applicable Reliability Standards. Unless otherwise agreed by the Parties, SMT shall own, operate, test and maintain appropriate metering equipment at the Point of Interconnection for each Generating Facility. Power flows to and from each Generating Facility shall be measured at the Points of Interconnection. Upon request, SMT will provide metering quantities, in analog and/or digital form, to BSMH and will telemeter such data to one or more locations designated by either Party. Such telemetered data shall be used, under normal operating conditions, as the official measurement of the amount of energy delivered from each Generating Facility to the Point of Interconnection. B. Reactive Power
Each Generating Facility will maintain a composite power delivery at continuous rated power output at its respective Point of Interconnection at a power factor within the range of 0.95 leading to 0.95 lagging. BSMH will operate the Generating Facilities to produce or absorb reactive power within these design limitations. If BSHM is unable to maintain the specified voltage or power factor, it shall promptly notify SMT.
C. Other Components
BSMH will maintain under-frequency and over-frequency relay set points for each Generating Facility as required by Applicable Reliability Standards to ensure ride through capability of the SMT Facilities.
Infrastructure security of transmission equipment and operations and control hardware and software is essential to ensure day-to-day transmission system reliability and operational security. FERC expects all transmission providers, market participants, and interconnection customers to comply with the recommendations offered by the Presidents Critical Infrastructure Protection Board and, eventually, best practice recommendations from the electric reliability authority. All public utilities will be expected to meet basic standards for system infrastructure and operational security, including physical, operational, and cyber-security practices.

Contract No. 4755 Rev. No. 2 SECOND AMENDED AND RESTATED INTERCONNECTION AGREEMENT Between TENNESSEE VALLEY AUTHORITY And SMOKY MOUNTAIN TRANSMISSION LLC
THIS AGREEMENT, made and entered into as of the 26th day of August, 2022, by and between TENNESSEE VALLEY AUTHORITY (TVA), a corporation created by and existing under and by virtue of the Tennessee Valley Authority Act of 1933, as amended (the TVA Act), and SMOKY MOUNTAIN TRANSMISSION LLC (SMT), a limited liability company created by and existing under the laws of the State of Delaware, as assignee of, ALCOA POWER GENERATING INC., formerly Tapoco, Inc. (APGI), a corporation created and existing under the State of Tennessee. TVA and SMT are also hereinafter sometimes referred to individually as Party and collectively as Parties. WITNESSETH: WHEREAS, TVA owns and operates electric facilities in the States of Kentucky, Tennessee, Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi, North Carolina, and Virginia; and WHEREAS, the TVA and APGI have previously entered into an agreement dated May 20, 2011, numbered 4755 (2011 Agreement), providing for, among other things, the coordinated operation of electrical system facilities owned by TVA and APGI, including the four hydroelectric generating facilities of the Tapoco Project, which is designated by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) as Project No. P-2169, and a 161-kV transmission system in Tennessee and western North Carolina; and WHEREAS, Brookfield Smoky Mountain Hydropower LP (BSMH) has acquired the Tapoco Project from APGI, and SMT has acquired the associated transmission system in Tennessee and western North Carolina (SMT Transmission System) from APGI (collectively, the Tapoco Project and the SMT Transmission Systems are defined as the Tapoco Power System); and WHEREAS, TVA, APGI, SMT, and BSMH have entered into an Assignment and Amendatory Agreement dated November 15, 2012, numbered 4755 supplement no. 1 (Assignment Agreement) pursuant to which TVA has consented to the assignment of the 2011 Agreement to SMT under the terms and conditions set forth in the Assignment Agreement; and WHEREAS, TVA, SMT, and BSMH have entered into an Amendatory Agreement dated August 26, 2022, numbered 4755 supplement no. 2 (Amendatory Agreement) to reflect that SMT is no longer a registered Transmission Service Provider (TSP) with the North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC) and no longer administers a FERC approved open access transmission tariff; and WHEREAS, TVA and SMT are entering into this second amended and restated agreement (Interconnection Agreement), to provide for the terms and conditions for the
continued interconnection, coordination, and operation of the TVA Transmission System and the Tapoco Power System; and WHEREAS, as of the Effective Date of this Interconnection Agreement, the Tapoco Power System, as defined below, will continue to operate within the TVA Balancing Authority Area; NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the above premises and of the agreements herein set forth, and subject to the provisions of the TVA Act, the Parties agree as follows: SECTION 1 DEFINITION OF TERMS 1.1 Tapoco Power System means the four developments of BSMHs Tapoco Project, P-2169, and the 161-kV transmission system owned by the SMT in Tennessee and western North Carolina. 1.2 SMT Transmission System means those transmission, substation, and related facilities within the Tapoco Power System owned and operated by SMT. 1.3 Balancing Authority means the entity that integrates resource plans ahead of time, maintains load-interchange-generation balance, and supports interconnection frequency in real time. 1.4 Balancing Authority Area means the collection of generation, transmission, and loads within the metered boundary of the Balancing Authority. The Balancing Authority maintains load-resource balance within this area. 1.5 Central Time means Central Standard Time or Central Daylight Savings Time, whichever is then prevailing for the TVA Transmission System. 1.6 Commercially Reasonable means, with respect to any action required to be made, attempted, or taken by a Party under this Interconnection Agreement, such efforts as a reasonably prudent business would undertake for the protection of its own interests under the conditions affecting such action, including the time for notice in advance of the need to take such action, the duration and type of such action, the competitive environment in which such action occurs, and the cost and risk to the Party required to take such action. The Party carrying out such efforts or action should endeavor, to the extent practical, to (i) coordinate with the other Party in order to minimize any adverse impact on the other Party and (ii) mitigate the cost impact on the other Party, including consultation with the other Party as to reasonable alternative plans or actions for cost mitigation. 1.7 Confidential Information has the meaning set forth in Section 14.1. 1.8 Curtail or Curtailment has the meaning set forth in Section 7.4. 1.9 Day means the period beginning at 00:00 and ending at 12:00 midnight Central Time. 1.10 Designated Output has the meaning set forth in Section 10.1 1.11 Difference has the meaning set forth in Section 10.1. 2
1.12 Disconnect or Disconnection has the meaning set forth in Section 7.4. 1.13 Effective Date means the date specified in Section 2.1. 1.14 Emergency means any abnormal system condition, including voltage abnormalities, associated with the transmission and distribution of electricity that requires automatic or prompt manual action to prevent or limit damage to persons or property, loss of transmission facilities or generation supply that could likely adversely affect or is imminently likely to adversely affect the Tapoco Power System, the reliability of the TVA Transmission System, the SMT Transmission System, the systems to which the TVA Transmission System and SMT Transmission System are each directly or indirectly connected, or TVA or SMTs ability to maintain safe, adequate, and continuous electric service to its customers consistent with Good Utility Practice. 1.15 ERO means the organization certified by FERC under Section 215 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. §824o(c), the purpose of which is to establish and enforce reliability standards for the bulk-power system, subject to FERCs review. 1.16 Exhibit RD means Exhibit RD to this Interconnection Agreement, entitled 'Rate for Difference Between Scheduled Amount and Generation Output,' as modified, changed, replaced, or adjusted by TVA from time to time. 1.17 FERC means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any such successor regulatory agency. 1.18 Facility Electrical Output means the actual amount of net electrical power generated by BSMHs generating facilities within the Tapoco Power System. 1.19 Force Majeure has the meaning set forth in Section 16.1. 1.20 Good Utility Practice means any of the practices, methods, and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or practices, methods, and acts that, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety, and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to any particular set of optimum practices, methods, or acts to the exclusion of all others, but rather is intended to include a spectrum of acceptable practices, methods, and acts generally accepted in the region in which the Tapoco Power System is located. 1.21 Guidelines means TVA's Transmission Service Guidelines, as such Guidelines now exist or may hereafter be modified, or any replacement document providing for transmission service over the TVA Transmission System. 1.22 Guarantor shall have the meaning set forth in Section 15. 1.23 NERC shall mean the North American Electric Reliability Corporation, the current ERO. 1.24 Operating Committee has the meaning set forth in Section 6.1. 3
1.25 Operating Procedures has the meaning set forth in Section 6.2. 1.26 Other Systems has the meaning set forth in Section 7.4(d). 1.27 Performance Assurance means collateral in the form of either cash, letter(s) of credit, or other security or combination thereof, reasonably acceptable to TVA as may be required as security under this Interconnection Agreement. 1.28 Point of Interconnection or Points of Interconnection shall mean the point or points at which the TVA Transmission System and SMT Transmission System are connected as specified in Section 3 and Exhibit FC, as such point or points may be added, deleted, or otherwise changed from time to time in accordance with this Interconnection Agreement. 1.29 Reliability Coordinator shall mean the entity that is the highest level of authority who is responsible for the reliable operation of the bulk electric system, has the wide area view of the bulk electric system, and has the operating tools, processes and procedures, including the authority to prevent or mitigate emergency operating situations in both next-day analysis and real-time operations. 1.30 Reliability Coordination Agreement has the meaning set forth in Section 8. 1.31 SERC shall mean the SERC Reliability Corporation, which serves as a regional entity, as defined in 16 U.S.C. § 824o(a)(7), with delegated authority from NERC for the purpose of proposing and enforcing reliability standards within the SERC region, or any successor regional entity. 1.32 Tie Line means a circuit connecting two Balancing Authority Areas. 1.33 TVA Act means the Tennessee Valley Authority Act of 1933, as amended (16 U.S.C. §§ 831-831ee). 1.34 TVA Transmission System means those transmission, substation, and related facilities owned and operated by TVA. SECTION 2 TERM OF AGREEMENT
2.1 Initial Term and Extensions. This Interconnection Agreement is effective as of November 1, 2021 (the "Effective Date"); provided, however, that SMT shall file this Interconnection Agreement with FERC to amend the interconnection agreement previously filed with FERC in Docket No. ER13-402-000 and any changes in the terms and conditions of any service provided by SMT shall become effective on the date specified by FERC, and shall continue in effect for an initial term ending on July 1, 2031. At the end of the initial term of this Interconnection Agreement, this Interconnection Agreement shall continue in effect from year to year thereafter unless terminated by either Party as provided for in Section 2.2 below. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Sections 7 and 10 of this Interconnection Agreement shall be in effect during the term of this Interconnection Agreement only for such periods and to the extent the Tapoco Power System operates within the TVA Balancing Authority Area. 4
2.2 Termination by Either Party. Either Party may terminate this Interconnection Agreement at the end of the initial term hereof or at any time thereafter upon one year's prior written notice to the other Party.
SECTION 3 POINTS OF INTERCONNECTION AND FACILITIES
3.1 Points of Interconnection. The respective transmission systems of TVA and SMT shall be connected at the following locations: (a) The points at which TVA's 161-kV facilities connect to SMT's 161-kV facilities at APGI's South Plant Substation (also known as the Alcoa Primary Substation and the Alcoa 161-kV Substation); (b) The terminus of TVA's Fontana-Santeetlah 161-kV Line at the Santeetlah Hydro Plant Switchyard; and (c) Such additional Points of Interconnection, if any, as may hereinafter be established and included herein by agreement of the Parties. 3.2 Incorporation of Exhibit FC. Exhibit FC, which is attached to and made a part of this Interconnection Agreement, is a facilities configuration sketch that depicts, at a very high level, the physical connection of certain major facilities of the Parties and identifies the Points of Interconnection between TVA's and SMTs respective systems.
3.3 Access to Facilities. Each Party shall have free right of access to its facilities installed on the premises of the other Party. Any equipment or facilities installed by either TVA or SMT on the property of the other shall be considered to be the property of the Party furnishing the equipment or facilities.
3.4 Operation and Maintenance. Each Party shall operate and maintain its respective facilities in accordance with Good Utility Practice and the other provisions of this Interconnection Agreement, as well as any applicable laws and regulations.
SECTION 4 SERVICE CONDITIONS
4.1 Connected Operation of Systems.
The TVA Transmission System and SMT Transmission System shall be and shall remain connected at the Points of Interconnection described in Section 3.1 hereof, insofar as, in the sole opinion of either TVA or SMT, this can be done without jeopardy to its system, impairment of reliable service to its customers, or creating an undue electrical burden on the system of either TVA or SMT. If, in the sole opinion of either TVA or SMT, any operating conditions or circumstances may jeopardize its system, impair reliable service, or otherwise create an undue electrical burden on its system, then that Party 5
shall have the right to open the connection to avoid such consequences and to maintain the connection open until the conditions or circumstances creating the problem have been eliminated. Prior notice shall be given to the other Party when practical before either Party opens a Point of Interconnection or it is reclosed after it has been opened.
Except as otherwise provided in this Section 4.1 and in Section 7.4, the TVA Transmission System and SMT Transmission System shall be operated in continuous synchronism through the facilities used to establish the Points of Interconnection. If synchronous operation of the systems is interrupted either manually or automatically because of reasons beyond the control of either Party, or because of scheduled maintenance that has been agreed to by both Parties, the Parties shall cooperate to remove or mitigate the cause of such interruption as soon as practicable and restore normal operating conditions. Further, in addition to those situations addressed in Section 7.4, should conditions arise from disturbances on the interconnected network of which systems of the Parties are a part, or from other causes that would jeopardize either system, impair reliable service, or otherwise create an undue electrical burden on either or both systems, the Parties may jointly or separately take necessary action to interrupt synchronous operation. Neither Party shall be responsible to the other Party for any damage or loss of revenue caused by any such interruption.
4.2 Control of Facilities and System Disturbances.
TVA and SMT shall each retain sole control of its own facilities and the use thereof. Nothing in this Interconnection Agreement shall (a) require either Party to construct facilities primarily for the benefit of the other, (b) interfere with either Party's right to proceed with additions or alterations that such Party determines, in its sole discretion, are required to provide adequate and reliable service to its customers, and (c) require either Party to take any action that would, in its sole judgment, adversely affect its ability to maintain reliable service to its own customers.
Insofar as practicable, TVA and SMT shall protect, operate, and maintain their respective systems so as to avoid or minimize the likelihood of disturbances that might cause impairment of service in the other's system or in any system interconnected therewith.
4.3 Inadvertent Flows of Energy.
The Parties recognize that unscheduled energy may flow over their respective systems as an indirect, unavoidable, and unintentional consequence of the physical and electrical characteristics of the interconnected network of transmission lines of which the transmission systems of the Parties are a part. Each Party shall permit such flows to occur on its transmission system, subject, however, to the understanding that such flows shall not be of such magnitude or duration as to, in the sole judgment of either Party, jeopardize or adversely affect the ability of said Party to render proper service to its customers and to render or accept service to or from companies with which it now has, or at any time hereafter may have, contractual arrangements to furnish, take, or interchange power, or otherwise create an undue electrical burden on the system of either TVA or SMT.
Should such flows of energy become of such magnitude or duration, in the sole judgment of the Party over whose transmission facilities they occur, as to jeopardize or 6
adversely affect its ability to render proper service as set forth above, or otherwise create an undue electrical burden on the system of either TVA or SMT, the Party whose system is causing such flows shall, upon being notified by the other Party to such effect, promptly undertake such action or actions as are necessary, practicable, and prudent to reduce such energy flows to a level acceptable to the affected Party. In the event that the Party so notified advises the other Party that it cannot in its judgment undertake such action or actions without jeopardizing reliability of service on its system, or will not for whatever reason undertake such action or actions, the affected Party may interrupt synchronous operation as it deems necessary.
Each Party hereto further recognizes that such flows may result in an increase in loading or losses on the transmission system of the other Party, which may be unduly burdensome to such other Party. When requested by either Party, the Parties shall meet and consider the factors involved, giving weight to the frequency, magnitude, and duration of such indicated increases, and shall endeavor to arrive at a mutually agreeable solution to relieve or address such burden, which may include equitable compensation to the affected Party. Absent such a mutually agreeable solution, the affected Party may interrupt synchronous operation as it deems appropriate, and as further provided in Section 4.1 above.
4.4 Conditions of Delivery.
Any power made available by a Party to the other Party hereunder shall be in the form of three-phase alternating current at a frequency of approximately 60 hertz. The power shall be delivered at the Points of Interconnection at the respective normal voltages of the transmission facilities serving the points of Interconnection or such other voltage as may be agreed upon by the Operating Representatives.
4.5 Kilovar Supply.
It is intended that neither Party shall impose an undue burden on the other with respect to the flow of kilovars. The Operating Committee representatives shall establish from time to time mutually satisfactory voltage schedules and kilovar supply arrangements.

practices of TVA's Balancing Authority Area and in compliance with the applicable provisions of TVA's standard metering procedures entitled "IPP, Distributed Generation, Interchange, and TVA Generation Metering Requirements," as such document may be revised or replaced by TVA from time-to-time. 5.5 Accounting Adjustments.
If any tests or inspections under Section 5.4 above show either Party's measurements to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1 %), an offsetting adjustment shall be made in the Party's statements for any known or agreed period of inaccuracy; in the absence of such knowledge or agreement, the adjustment shall be limited to the 30-day period prior to the date of such tests. Any metering equipment found to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1 %) shall be promptly replaced, repaired, or readjusted by the Party owning such defective equipment.

SECTION 10 GENERATION DIFFERENCE
10.1 Generation Difference.
Any shortfall in Facility Electrical Output preventing BSMH from meeting its sale commitments to TVA or third parties shall be the sole responsibility of BSMH. Notwithstanding any other provisions of this Interconnection Agreement, except as agreed to by the Parties and consistent with applicable law, TVA shall at no time be obligated to deliver energy to third parties in amounts in excess of the actual generation that is scheduled and delivered to the TVA Balancing Authority Area ("Designated Output"). Consistent with Good Utility Practice, SMT or BSMH, as applicable, shall take all actions that are within its control and within the reasonable capabilities of BSMH's generating facilities within the Tapoco Power System to assure that during each hour the amount of Designated Output shall be equal to or greater than the schedule of energy (including any applicable transmission losses) delivered to said third parties. SMT shall immediately notify TVA of any circumstances that would cause the Designated Output to be less than the schedule of energy ("Difference") and shall take immediate corrective action. In order to account for said Difference, said schedule of energy shall be appropriately reduced as soon as possible by the Parties so that over the hour, as is reasonably practicable, the Designated Output is equal to or greater than the schedule of energy (including any applicable transmission losses). In the event a Difference nevertheless occurs over an hour between the scheduled amount and the Designated Output, SMT shall pay, or cause a third party to pay, the appropriate charges applied to said Difference; provided, however, that said charges shall be consistent with the imbalance charges applied to similar power production facilities located in the TVA Balancing Authority Area in comparable circumstances. In the event that the actual generation that is delivered exceeds the scheduled amount over an hour, TVA shall pay for such excess in accordance with TVA's current imbalance charges applied to said excess.

10.3 Facility Electrical Output.
For purposes of applying the provisions of Exhibit RD, TVA shall determine the amount, if any, of the Difference delivered to TVA for each clock hour during a billing month based on TVA's metering facilities located at the Points of Interconnection. To the extent that TVA's data may not be sufficient or otherwise available (such as due to equipment failure or malfunctioning), SMT shall supply TVA with backup or supplemental data (which are subject to review and verification by TVA for accuracy and authenticity) as 15
may be necessary or appropriate for TVA's billing purposes under this Interconnection Agreement.

Rate for Difference Between Scheduled Amount and Generation Output
I. Description: The rate described below is required under the interconnection agreement between TVA and the owner and operator of a generating facility located in TVA's Control Area and interconnected to the TVA system (Generator) when a difference occurs between the scheduled amount(s) of energy plus losses and the actual generation output (rounded to the nearest whole megawatt hour) of the Generator delivered to TVA within TVA's Control Area over a single hour (Difference). Scheduled amount(s) of energy shall include all schedules for delivery to any party, including TVA, at the point of connection to the TVA transmission system and for delivery outside the TVA Control Area. Where there is the potential during any hour for TVA charging a Transmission Customer for energy imbalance under Schedule 4 of TVA's Transmission Service Guidelines (Guidelines) or charging the Generator for a Difference under this Exhibit RD, TVA may either charge the Transmission Customer for energy imbalance under the Schedule 4 or the Generator for a Difference under this Exhibit RD, but not both, unless application of both charges is needed to compensate TVA for the imbalance. The terms and charges set forth below will apply to the Difference.
In determining the appropriate charges for the Difference, TVA will apply a three band pricing structure as described in Sections II, III, and IV below. The appropriate charges will be determined by either the Generator's percentage deviation from the scheduled amount(s) of energy plus losses or the megawatt hour deviation. If the Difference exceeds either the percentage limits or the megawatt hour limits for a deviation band, the charges for the Difference will be based on higher band charges.
II. Treatment of the Difference Within Deviation Band I: If the Difference is less than or equal to +/- one and five-tenths percent (1.5%) of the scheduled energy plus losses and the deviation is 2 MWh or less, the Generator will be subject to the charges for the Difference set for below:
A. If the output of the generation integrated over a clock hour is greater than the scheduled energy plus losses over a clock hour, TVA will pay the Generator 100 percent of TVA's decremental cost for the clock hour applied to the Difference.
B. If the scheduled energy plus losses is greater than the output of the generation integrated over a clock hour, the Generator will pay TVA 100 percent of TVA's incremental costs for the clock hour applied to the Difference.
Differences that are within one and five-tenths percent (1.5%) of the scheduled energy plus losses but that exceed 2 MWh will fall into Band II if the deviation is greater than 2 MWh and less than or equal to 10 MWh or into Band III if the deviation is greater than 10 MWh. Likewise, Differences that are less than or equal to 2 MWh but greater than one and five-tenths percent (1.5%) of the scheduled energy plus losses will fall into Band II if the deviation is greater than 1.5% and less than or equal to 7.5% of the scheduled energy or into Band III if the deviation is greater than 7.5% of the scheduled energy plus losses.
III. Treatment of the Difference Within Deviation Band II: If the Difference is greater than +/- one and five-tenths percent (1.5%) and less than or equal to seven and five-tenths percent (7.5%) of the scheduled energy plus losses, or if the Difference is greater than 2 MWh and less than or equal to 10 MWh, the Generator will be subject to the charges for the Difference set forth below:
A. If the output of the generation integrated over a clock hour is greater than the scheduled energy plus losses over a clock hour, TVA will pay the Generator 90 percent of TVA's RD-1
decremental cost for the clock hour applied to the Difference. The Generator is also responsible for any additional costs directly attributable to its generation output that exceeds the scheduled amount plus losses by an excess 1.5% (e.g., if this occurs during a load turndown period where units are at minimum generation, units may have to be taken off line, there may be forced pumping out of economic order at TVA's pumped storage facility to increase the load, interchange power may be sold at less than marginal cost to supply, etc.).
B. If the scheduled energy plus losses is greater than the output of the generation integrated over a clock hour, the Generator will pay TVA 110 percent of TVA's incremental cost in the hour applied to the Difference.
Differences that are less than or equal to seven and five-tenths percent (7.5%) of the scheduled energy plus losses but greater than 10 MWh will fall into Band III. Likewise, Differences that are less than or equal to 10 MWh but greater than 7.5% of the scheduled energy plus losses will fall into Band III.
IV. Treatment of the Difference Within Deviation Band III: If the Difference is greater than +/- seven and five-tenths percent (7.5%) of the scheduled energy plus losses or if the Difference is greater than 10 MWh, the Transmission Customer will be subject to the charges for the Difference set forth below:
A. If the scheduled energy plus losses is greater than the load integrated over a clock hour, TVA will pay the Generator 75 percent of TVA's decremental cost for the clock hour applied to the Difference. The Generator is also responsible for any additional costs directly attributable to a schedule that exceeds the load by an excess of 1.5% (e.g., if this occurs during a load turndown period where units are at minimum generation, units may have to be taken off line, there may be forced pumping out of economic order at TVA's pumped storage facility to increase the load, interchange power may be sold at less than marginal cost, etc.).
B. If the load integrated over a clock hour is greater than the scheduled amount, the Generator will pay TVA 125 percent of TVA's incremental cost for the clock hour applied to the Difference.
V. Incremental and Decremental Cost: For purposes of this Schedule, incremental cost and decremental cost represent TVA's actual hourly cost of the last 20 MW dispatched to meet total demand on the system for any purpose including to supply TVA's Native Load Customers (as that term is defined in the Guidelines), correct imbalances, or make off-system sales, based on the replacement cost of fuel, unit heat rates, start-up costs (including any commitment and redispatch costs), incremental operation and maintenance costs, and purchased and interchange power costs, as applicable.
VI. Billing and Payment: Any billing and payment required herein shall be in accordance with the billing and payment provisions of the interconnection agreement. Additionally any payments due from TVA herein shall be rendered within 30 days following the end of the month in which the Difference occurred, provided however that if the amount of the payment by TVA is in dispute, the disputed amount shall not be due until resolution of the dispute.
VII. Modification of Rate: This rate is subject to modification, as determined by TVA.
